      <li>
        The camping! Some people visit Abel Tasman National Park for a
        wonderful camping experience. There are campsites dotted all along the
        track, some right next to beautiful golden beaches.
      </li>
      <li>
        Rest your weary walking feet at Onetahuti Beach. Shaped like a horseshoe,
        it&rsquo;s one of the longest and most beautiful beaches in the park. Swim,
        snorkel or soak up the sunshine!
      </li>
      <li>
        A 20 minute walk crosses a low ridge from Anchorage Hut to crescent-shaped Te
        Pukatea Bay. From there, a 1 hour walk with great views leads to Pitt Head, an
        old pa site, and back to Anchorage.
      </li>
      <li>
        Tonga Island Marine Reserve is the third marine reserve to be created
        alongside a national park and covers an area of 1835 hectares. Swimming,
        snorkelling and kayaking are popular activities in the reserve.
      </li>
      <li>
        Swim at Cleopatra&rsquo;s Pool, a natural rock pool with a moss-lined
        waterslide that is fit for a queen! From Torrent Bay estuary, a 20 minute walk
        takes you to this refreshing pool.
      </li>
